When formula_65 then formula_56 is said to be formula_51

Absolute continuity of measures is reflexive and transitive, but is not antisymmetric, so it is a preorder rather than a partial order. Instead, if formula_68 and formula_69 the measures formula_28 and formula_56 are said to be equivalent. Thus absolute continuity induces a partial ordering of such equivalence classes.

If formula_28 is a signed or complex measure, it is said that formula_28 is absolutely continuous with respect to formula_56 if its variation formula_75 satisfies formula_76 equivalently, if every set formula_45 for which formula_78 is formula_28-null.

The Radon–Nikodym theorem states that if formula_28 is absolutely continuous with respect to formula_81 and both measures are σ-finite, then formula_28 has a density, or &quot;Radon-Nikodym derivative&quot;, with respect to formula_81 which means that there exists a formula_56-measurable function formula_85 taking values in formula_86 denoted by formula_87 such that for any formula_56-measurable set formula_45 we have:
